<DOC><DOCNO> WSJ880603-0167 </DOCNO><HL> Westinghouse Credit Buys Boeing Aircraft To Lease to USAir Inc. </HL><SO> </SO><CO> WX BA U </CO><IN> AIR ARO </IN><DATELINE> PITTSBURGH  </DATELINE><TEXT>   Westinghouse Credit Corp., a unit of Westinghouse Electric Corp., said it purchased Boeing Co. aircraft for $182 million to lease to USAir Inc. and its Piedmont Aviation unit.    Westinghouse Credit said it purchased seven Boeing 737-300 aircraft. Four of those planes will be leased to USAir, with the others leased to Piedmont.    Separately, Westinghouse Credit also arranged to purchase as many as 10 SD3-60 aircraft for $50 million from Short Brothers PLC. Those aircraft, in turn, will be leased to regional carriers in the U.S.    Westinghouse Credit is a business-finance concern with assets of more than $6 billion. At the end of 1987, its lease portfolio of equipment, mostly aircraft, had an original acquisition cost of more than $2 billion.    Westinghouse stock fell 62.5 cents to close at $52.875 and Boeing stock declined 12.5 cents to close at $55, both in New York Stock Exchange composite trading yesterday. </TEXT></DOC>